Date: Sat, 07 Mar 1998 13:19:33 GMT
From: jralphb@easynet.co.uk (J Ralph Blanchfield)
Source: PA News report, via FSNET dated 6 March

Investigators attached to the U.K. BSE inquiry, which starts on Monday, were
combing through files at the Treasury today as part of what this story
called an unprecedented search of Government departments. Teams of
"para-legals" (young helpers with legal training working under the
supervision of experienced lawyers) have been set to work sifting through
thousands of documents locked away in Whitehall vaults. Armed with laptop
computers, they are looking for anything which might shed light on events
leading up to the beef crisis, and linking pieces of the jigsaw together.
The aim of the deep probing inquiry, headed by Appeal Court judge Lord
Justice Phillips, is to explore the root causes of "mad cow disease" and the
former Tory Government's handling of the crisis. Today it emerged that the
inquiry, which will hear evidence from former ministers and senior civil
servants, is expected to cost more than 2 million. Much of the money will
ultimately come from the tax payer. The five Government departments involved
(the Department of Health, Ministry of Agriculture and Welsh, Scottish and
Northern Ireland offices) are meeting their own costs.
The inquiry team has received more than 500 submissions from members of the
public, ranging from letters to 200-page documents. The investigators have
sought evidence from more than 100 scientists and members of the rendering
food (sic) industry and written to more than 300 ministers, ex-ministers and
civil servants. The team has been given unfettered access to Government
files, and so far has not encountered any resistance from ministers or
officials.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
The formal hearings of the official BSE Inquiry begins on Monday 9 March
1998. As indicated in Lord Justice Phillips's opening speech the daily
transcripts of evidence will be put on a dedicated Web site at
<http://www.bse.org.uk>. This has already been set up. It already contains
useful background information relating to the Inquiry itself and the history
of BSE.
--
J Ralph Blanchfield, MBE
Food Science, Food Technology & Food Law Consultant
Chair, IFST External Affairs
Web Editor, Institute of Food Science & Technology
